BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:ESS Oral Defense - Matthew Worden - Y2E2 299 @ 2:30 PM
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260501T213000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260501T223000
DTSTAMP:20260516T064814Z
UID:2e2de5b3fc9f4266@gid-seminars.wnprc.wisc.edu
CATEGORIES:PhD Defense
DESCRIPTION:Stanford University\n\n*** Ph.D. Thesis/ Oral Defense ***\n\nF
 ROM SITE TO SATELLITE: INFERRING PLANT CARBON ALLOCATION SHIFTS WITH MODEL
 -DATA FUSION IN SOUTH AMERICA AND AFRICA\n\n \n\n Matthew Worden\n\nFriday
 \, May 1\,  2:30 PM\n\nY2E2 299\n\nDepartment of Earth System Science\n\nA
 dvisor: Dr. Alex Konings\n\nDrought can alter plant carbon allocation\, th
 e partitioning of photosynthetically assimilated carbon among plant organs
  and respiration. In turn\, shifts in allocation can influence carbon pool
 s and fluxes for years after drought\, motivating their quantification. Ho
 wever\, allocation responses to drought remain difficult to measure\, are 
 spatially variable across existing studies\, and are particularly sparsely
  quantified in the tropics. These limitations hinder efforts to explain tr
 opical carbon cycle responses to drought. To address this gap\, this disse
 rtation develops and applies a model–data fusion approach to infer alloc
 ation dynamics from existing site and satellite observations of carbon and
  water fluxes and states rather than from direct measurements of carbon al
 location. \n\nI use the CARbon DAta MOdel fraMework (CARDAMOM)\, which cou
 ples a process-based ecosystem model with Bayesian inference to retrieve o
 ptimized ecosystem parameters and initial states from observational constr
 aints. I introduce a representation of carbon allocation as a function of 
 soil water availability within CARDAMOM. I then assimilate flux tower obse
 rvations at Guyaflux\, French Guiana followed by satellite-based observati
 ons across South America and Africa. At Guyaflux\, I first demonstrate the
  robustness of my approach. I then show that inferred allocation shifts in
 creased the cumulative magnitude of drought recovery effects by about a fa
 ctor of 2.8\, extended average recovery time by roughly five months\, and 
 accounted for 65% [46%–75%] of modeled drought legacy effects in net bio
 sphere exchange. Mechanistically\, these legacy effects arose because allo
 cation shifts altered both foliage and fine-root pool\n\nEvent URL: https:
 //events.stanford.edu/event/copy-of-ess-oral-defense-angela-tsao-y2e2-300-
 1-2pm\n\nSource: stanford_virtual
LOCATION:Y2E2 Building\, 299
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/copy-of-ess-oral-defense-angela-tsao
 -y2e2-300-1-2pm
BEGIN:VALARM
ACTION:DISPLAY
DESCRIPTION:Reminder: ESS Oral Defense - Matthew Worden - Y2E2 299 @ 2:30 
 PM
TRIGGER:-PT1H
END:VALARM
END:VEVENT
