SUMMARY:CFAR Seminar with Dr. Brooke Nichols - May 21\, 2026
DTSTART;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260521T190000
DTEND;TZID=America/Los_Angeles:20260521T203000
DTSTAMP:20260516T064814Z
UID:da5b541b7bd6067d@gid-seminars.wnprc.wisc.edu
CATEGORIES:Fred Hutch Center for AIDS Research (CFAR)
DESCRIPTION:Event interval: Single day event\nOnline Meeting Link: https:/
 /washington.zoom.us/meeting/register/h92B3kzpRjy3zxG0GFjrXw\nAccessibility
  Contact: g0201@uw.edu\nEvent Types: Lectures/Seminars\n\nREGISTER NOW! \n
 Register via this link for virtual attendance \nzoom registration: \nhttps
 ://washington.zoom.us/meeting/register/h92B3kzpRjy3zxG0GFjrXw \n12:00pm - 
 1:30pm \n\n*Please note that this Seminar will be taking place earlier in 
 the day than usual in order to accommodate our speaker who will be joining
  us from a different time zone* \n\n12:30pm - 1:30pm \nVIRTUAL \nCFAR Semi
 nar Speaker: Brooke Nichols \nTalk Title: Complexity in the Right Places: 
 Reorienting HIV Models for Implementation \nBio:  \nBrooke Nichols\, PhD\,
  MSc\, is an Associate Professor of Global Health at Boston University Sch
 ool of Public Health and an infectious disease mathematical modeller and h
 ealth economist based. Her research sits at the intersection of transmissi
 on dynamics\, implementation modelling\, and health economics\, using quan
 titative approaches to answer practical questions about how HIV\, tubercul
 osis\, antimicrobial resistance\, and other pathogens can be tackled more 
 effectively in real-world health systems. Her work has shaped national and
  global health policy across several domains\, including WHO Target Produc
 t Profiles for diagnostics\, normative guidance on HIV prevention and care
 \, and global strategies for optimal diagnostic use during the COVID-19 pa
 ndemic. \n \n12:00pm - 12:30pm\nVIRTUAL \nNew Faces Speaker: Khai Hoan Tra
 m \nTalk Title: Modeling the Fallout: Projecting the Global Impact of US F
 unding Cuts \nBio:  \nDr. Tram\, MD\, MS\, is an infectious diseases physi
 cian-scientist in the Division of Allergy & Infectious Diseases at the Uni
 versity of Washington. He conducts research on HIV and TB and practices me
 dicine at Harborview Medical Center and UW Medical Center. He sees patient
 s weekly at the Madison HIV Clinic. Dr. Tram attended Stanford University 
 medical school and completed Internal Medicine residen\n\nEvent URL: https
 ://washington.zoom.us/meeting/register/h92B3kzpRjy3zxG0GFjrXw\n\nSource: u
 w_cfar
LOCATION:Online
URL:https://washington.zoom.us/meeting/register/h92B3kzpRjy3zxG0GFjrXw
